Part 1: Selecting the Data

if the geo meta sqlite database has not been downloaded, download it

if (!file.exists('GEOmetadb.sqlite')) {
    GEOmetadb::getSQLiteFile()
}

This is the SQL query that I used to search for, a few thing that are different from code given in lecture, I only select those with a PubMed id to ensure there is a publication associated with the dataset, and where the supplementary file is like “count” to ensure it does not just have a raw file, and it is not connected with cancer, tumor, or stem cell, and SARS-CoV-2, but is connected to gene therapy

con <- DBI::dbConnect(RSQLite::SQLite(),'GEOmetadb.sqlite')

sql <- paste("SELECT DISTINCT gse.title, gse.gse, gse.supplementary_file, gse.pubmed_id, gpl.title
              FROM gse 
              INNER JOIN gse_gpl ON gse.gse = gse_gpl.gse
              INNER JOIN gpl ON gse_gpl.gpl = gpl.gpl
              WHERE gpl.technology = 'high-throughput sequencing'
              AND gpl.organism = 'Homo sapiens'
              AND gse.pubmed_id is NOT NULL
              AND gse.submission_date > '2015-01-01'
              AND gse.supplementary_file is NOT NULL
              AND gse.supplementary_file LIKE '%count%'
              AND gse.title NOT LIKE '%cancer%'
              AND gse.title NOT LIKE '%tumor%'
              AND gse.title NOT LIKE '%stem cells%'
              AND gse.title NOT LIKE '%SARS-CoV-2%'
              AND gse.title LIKE '%gene therapy%'")

queryResults <- DBI::dbGetQuery(con, sql)
queryResults
DBI::dbDisconnect(con)

and there was only 2, and I chose the one on LCA.

Part 10 interpreting the data

First of all, I want to clarify that although the associated publication has both bulk RNA-seq and single cell RNA-seq, the dataset series GSE153099 is the one for single cell (it specifically mentions this in its overall design section on GEO) and the dataset series GSE152939 is bulk RNA-seq, which contain 2 data set separate by which mutation is being tested on.

In simple terms, leber congenital amaurosis (LCA) is an eye disease that causes vision loss, most cases of LCA are caused by mutation(s) in Cone-rod homeobox (CRX). Normally LCA is a autosomal recessive disease, but some of the mutation in some genes can make it autosomal dominant, CRX is an example of such gene.

There are 2 mutation that were of interest in this study, I138fs and K88N In mutation nomenclature it is c.G264T (p.K88N) or c.413delT (p.I138fs48). Translated into English the first mutation means in the coding DNA, guanine at position 264 has been substituted with Adenine, this results a mutation in the corresponding protein’s, which is that lysine at position 88 has been substituted with Asparagine. The English translation of the second mutation, is that in the coding DNA, Thymine at position 413 was deleted, and thus in the protein start from the Isoleucine at position 138, there is a been frame shift of 48 amino acid.

  1. What are the control and test conditions of the dataset?

    The test condition is a retinal organoid derived from a induced pluripotent stem cells which is derived from a LCA-dominant patient with a mutation in CRX (specifically I138fs48). The control is another retinal organoid derived from induced pluripotent stem cells which is the healthy parent of the patient.

  2. Why is the dataset of interest to you?

    I was initially interested because it talks about gene therapy, which from my perspective is something that directly remove the cause of the disease, by changing the gene. It is the ultimate “treat the cause, not the symptom” treatment. As I was reading the paper, I was amazed that it has so many different things, like organoids, IPSC, bulk RNA-seq, single cell RNA-seq. Maybe it is just me, but I have never seems these terms mention in the same paper.

  3. Were there expression values that were not unique for specific genes?

    Yes, for the HGNC symbols, CCDC3, LINC01238, POLR2J3, POLR2J4, TBCE, they each map to 2 ensemble ids,

  4. Were there expression values that could not be mapped to current HUGO symbols?

    Yes, there was about 90+2281=2371 (This comes from 90 ensemble ids that are not in the mapping and 2281 where the corresponding HGNC symbol is empty) ensemble ids that is like. There are 19422 ensemble ids, only 17051 are mapped to current HUGO symbols, this is not too surprising as the associated publication was published on January 28, 2021, and the dataset was last updated on GEO on February 17, 2021 and it is February 15, 2022 at the time of writing this report, so the dataset was not too outdated.

  5. How many outliers were removed?

    None, because I do not have any reason to believe a measurement error has occurred

  6. How did you handle replicates?

    As mentioned in control vs test question, we have 1 pairs of parent and child. 3 organoid were each derived from the parent and the child for a total of 6 organoids. Then each organoid was measured at day 90, day 125, day 150, day 200. I think that a different organoid does mean a different biological replicate, though I am not sure in the event that control and test comes from different individuals, does that count as different biological replicates, but if that is the case, then we have 6 biological replicates, else we just have 3. Also, I am almost sure that the retinal organoid from different days are not considered biologically different. For measurement between different organoids, they are unpaired, and the same organoid, paired. I think there are no technical replicates in this file. None of the replicate were outlines, with respect to their own time and condition.

  7. What is the final coverage of your dataset?

    Around 19422 genes after filtering out low counts
